# Algorithms Before Computers

![Flowchart showing input, an ordered rule, and a result](../../../assets/images/algorithms.jpg)

An algorithm is a repeatable procedure for solving a problem. Recipes, arithmetic methods, and logical rules existed long before electronic machines.

Computer science did not begin when electronic computers filled rooms. An algorithm is a sequence of steps for transforming inputs into results, and people have designed such procedures for thousands of years. A recipe, a long-division method, a set of rules for a calendar, or a procedure for balancing accounts can all be studied in terms of inputs, operations, order, and expected output. The word “algorithm” is connected to the Latinized name of the mathematician al-Khwarizmi, whose work helped transmit systematic calculation traditions.

This history matters because it separates computation from the machine that executes it. A machine can make a procedure fast, repeatable, and scalable, but the procedure still has to be designed and interpreted. It also reminds us that computer history is global: Greek, Indian, Islamic, Chinese, African, European, and many other mathematical traditions contributed ideas later connected to computing.

The portrait is a modern representation rather than a photograph of al-Khwarizmi. That is a useful warning about historical images: illustrations can communicate an idea while carrying little direct evidence about a person’s appearance.

> **Further reading.** [Research source](https://computerhistory.org/blog/the-neverending-quest-for-firsts/)
